This repo holds my Claude Code presets — agents, slash commands, and the
global CLAUDE.md memory file — so I can sync them into any environment
in a single step.

Two install paths, depending on what you want:

  - `bootstrap.sh`    -> one-shot manual sync into `~/.claude/`
  - `install-hook.sh` -> per-project hook that auto-syncs every session

## Path 1: One-shot manual install

Paste this into a Claude Code session, or run it in any shell:

    curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/agastyataqi/trial4claudeforworkidkwhatimdoingatallsoimavibecodernow/main/bootstrap.sh | bash

It pulls the latest `main` and copies into `~/.claude/`:

  - `.claude/agents/`   -> `~/.claude/agents/`
  - `.claude/commands/` -> `~/.claude/commands/`
  - `CLAUDE.md`         -> `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md`

Idempotent. Safe to re-run any time to refresh.

### Caveat: restart Claude Code after running it

Claude Code scans `~/.claude/commands/` and `~/.claude/agents/` **once,
at session startup**, to build the slash-command registry. Files that
arrive after that scan — including files copied by this one-liner —
will **not** appear as `/commands` in the current session.

Workflow:

  1. Open Claude Code in the new project.
  2. Run the one-liner above as your first prompt.
  3. **Close Claude Code and reopen it.**
  4. Slash commands and CLAUDE.md memory are now active in the new session.

If you ever need a command in the *same* session you just installed
into, ask Claude in plain English ("run the council workflow on X") —
Claude can read the command file directly without going through the
slash registry.

## Path 2: Per-project hook (recommended for projects you reuse)

Run this **once per project repo** to drop a `SessionStart` hook into
the project's `.claude/settings.json`. From then on, every session in
that project auto-syncs presets at startup — no manual prompt needed.

    curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/agastyataqi/trial4claudeforworkidkwhatimdoingatallsoimavibecodernow/main/install-hook.sh | bash

Behaviour:

  - If `.claude/settings.json` does not exist: creates it with the hook.
  - If it exists and `jq` is installed: merges the hook in idempotently.
  - If it exists and `jq` is missing: prints the hook block for you to
    paste in manually.

After running, **commit `.claude/settings.json`** so the hook follows
the repo across machines and collaborators.

### Why this fixes the disappearing-commands problem

On Claude Code on the web, each session lives in its own container.
`~/.claude/` survives only as long as the parent session it was
populated in. Delete that session and new sessions start clean.

A `SessionStart` hook re-runs in every session — it re-fetches the
presets from `main` on startup, so you never depend on a parent
session's filesystem state. Hooks also fire **before** the
slash-command registry scan, so commands are available immediately —
no restart needed.

## Inside this repo

This repo's own `.claude/settings.json` already has the hook, so
working here just works out of the box.
